<subSubSection id="F8D8653EA775BE3AFF0BFBA4420A26B8" pageId="3" pageNumber="195" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="B07D36B5A775BE3AFF0BFBA4420A26B8" blockId="3.[151,1437,870,1509]" pageId="3" pageNumber="195">
<emphasis id="82B6EAA7A775BE3AFF0BFBA440672768" bold="true" box="[199,315,1051,1077]" pageId="3" pageNumber="195">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="77C24D36A775BE3AFE88FBA443152768" authorityName="H. Kobayashi" authorityYear="1989" box="[324,585,1051,1077]" class="Insecta" family="Cetoniidae" genus="Platysodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="195" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="formosanus">
<emphasis id="82B6EAA7A775BE3AFE88FBA443152768" box="[324,585,1051,1077]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="195">Platysodes formosanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is extremely similar to 
<taxonomicName id="77C24D36A775BE3AFC97FBA442962769" authorityName="Arrow, M. O. de Lisle" authorityYear="1910" box="[859,970,1051,1076]" class="Insecta" family="Cetoniidae" genus="Platysodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="195" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jansoni">
<emphasis id="82B6EAA7A775BE3AFC97FBA442962769" box="[859,970,1051,1076]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="195">P. jansoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the parameres of both also show no differences (
<figureCitation id="28F92A30A775BE3AFEEFFB8040F02704" box="[291,428,1087,1113]" captionStart="FIGURES 9–17" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1868,1892]" captionTargetBox="[221,1368,275,1835]" captionTargetId="figure-69@4.[213,1374,273,1845]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 9–17. Specimens of Platysodes Westwood, 1873. 9–12, P. formosanus Kobayashi, 1990: 9, female habitus (MYNU); 10–11, slightly greasy male and distal declivity of elytra (CKSJ); 12, parameres of holotype in apical view (MSMT; provided by Yu-Tang Wang). 13–17, P. jansoni Arrow, 1910: 13, greasy female with two maculae on elytron (BPBM; provided by James H. Boone); 14, female habitus (CKSJ); 15–16, male habitus and distal declivity of elytra (MNHN); 17, parameres in apical view (provided by Christophe Rivier). Red arrows emphasize the tomentose maculae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4301819" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4301819/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="195">Figs. 12, 17</figureCitation>
), and that resulted in 
<bibRefCitation id="D4534B44A775BE3AFD6FFB80423C2704" author="Qiu, J. Y. &amp; Xu, H. &amp; Chen, L." box="[675,864,1086,1113]" pageId="3" pageNumber="195" pagination="553 - 564" refId="ref4697" refString="Qiu, J. Y., Xu, H. &amp; Chen, L. (2015) Review of the Oriental genus Platysodes Westwood (Coleoptera: Scarabaeidae: Cetoniinae: Cremastocheilini) with a redescription of Platysodes madoni Bourgoin. Zootaxa, 4021 (4), 553 - 564. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4021.4.5" type="journal article" year="2015">
Qiu 
<emphasis id="82B6EAA7A775BE3AFD18FB8042512704" box="[724,781,1087,1113]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="195">et al.</emphasis>
(2015)
</bibRefCitation>
presumed them as the same species. Traditionally, the former is characterized by elytron bearing one tomentose macula and restricted to 
<collectingCountry id="C8D57625A775BE3AFBBFFBDC444E2720" box="[1139,1298,1123,1149]" name="Taiwan Island" pageId="3" pageNumber="195">Taiwan Island</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="D4534B44A775BE3AFAEFFBDC418E27FC" author="Kobayashi, H." pageId="3" pageNumber="195" pagination="73 - 81" refId="ref4670" refString="Kobayashi, H. (1990) Four new scarabaeid beetles (Coleoptera, Scarabaeidae) from Taiwan. Elytra, 18, 73 - 81." type="journal article" year="1990">Kobayashi 1990</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="D4534B44A775BE3AFF12FB3840D727FC" author="Qiu, J. Y. &amp; Xu, H. &amp; Chen, L." box="[222,395,1158,1185]" pageId="3" pageNumber="195" pagination="553 - 564" refId="ref4697" refString="Qiu, J. Y., Xu, H. &amp; Chen, L. (2015) Review of the Oriental genus Platysodes Westwood (Coleoptera: Scarabaeidae: Cetoniinae: Cremastocheilini) with a redescription of Platysodes madoni Bourgoin. Zootaxa, 4021 (4), 553 - 564. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4021.4.5" type="journal article" year="2015">
Qiu 
<emphasis id="82B6EAA7A775BE3AFEC3FB38401427FC" box="[271,328,1159,1185]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="195">et al.</emphasis>
2015
</bibRefCitation>
), while the latter is totally black and distributed in eastern 
<collectingCountry id="C8D57625A775BE3AFBD7FB38450927FC" box="[1051,1109,1159,1185]" name="India" pageId="3" pageNumber="195">India</collectingCountry>
and Indochina (
<bibRefCitation id="D4534B44A775BE3AFAC6FB3844CB27FC" author="Arrow, G. J." box="[1290,1431,1159,1185]" pageId="3" pageNumber="195" refId="ref4632" refString="Arrow, G. J. (1910) The Fauna of British India (Including Ceylon and Burma). Lamellicornia I (Cetoniinae and Dynastinae). Taylor &amp; Francis, London, 322 pp." type="book" year="1910">Arrow 1910</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="D4534B44A775BE3AFF5BFB1440142798" author="Qiu, J. Y. &amp; Xu, H. &amp; Chen, L." box="[151,328,1194,1221]" pageId="3" pageNumber="195" pagination="553 - 564" refId="ref4697" refString="Qiu, J. Y., Xu, H. &amp; Chen, L. (2015) Review of the Oriental genus Platysodes Westwood (Coleoptera: Scarabaeidae: Cetoniinae: Cremastocheilini) with a redescription of Platysodes madoni Bourgoin. Zootaxa, 4021 (4), 553 - 564. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4021.4.5" type="journal article" year="2015">
Qiu 
<emphasis id="82B6EAA7A775BE3AFF05FB14405F2798" box="[201,259,1195,1221]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="195">et al.</emphasis>
2015
</bibRefCitation>
). However, we recently obtained a female whose appearance perfectly matches the characteristics of 
<taxonomicName id="77C24D36A775BE3AFF79FB70400F27B4" authorityName="H. Kobayashi" authorityYear="1989" box="[181,339,1231,1257]" class="Insecta" family="Cetoniidae" genus="Platysodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="195" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="formosanus">
<emphasis id="82B6EAA7A775BE3AFF79FB70400F27B4" box="[181,339,1231,1257]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="195">P. formosanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="28F92A30A775BE3AFEADFB7040F927B4" box="[353,421,1231,1257]" captionStart="FIGURES 9–17" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1868,1892]" captionTargetBox="[221,1368,275,1835]" captionTargetId="figure-69@4.[213,1374,273,1845]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 9–17. Specimens of Platysodes Westwood, 1873. 9–12, P. formosanus Kobayashi, 1990: 9, female habitus (MYNU); 10–11, slightly greasy male and distal declivity of elytra (CKSJ); 12, parameres of holotype in apical view (MSMT; provided by Yu-Tang Wang). 13–17, P. jansoni Arrow, 1910: 13, greasy female with two maculae on elytron (BPBM; provided by James H. Boone); 14, female habitus (CKSJ); 15–16, male habitus and distal declivity of elytra (MNHN); 17, parameres in apical view (provided by Christophe Rivier). Red arrows emphasize the tomentose maculae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4301819" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4301819/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="195">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
), but it originated from Guangzhou (
<collectingRegion id="7206F857A775BE3AFCF2FB70429927B4" box="[830,965,1231,1257]" country="China" name="Guangdong" pageId="3" pageNumber="195">Guangdong</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry id="C8D57625A775BE3AFC1CFB70454927B7" box="[976,1045,1231,1258]" name="China" pageId="3" pageNumber="195">China</collectingCountry>
) where located on the southeastern edge of the Asian continent and between the Indochinese Peninsula and 
<collectingCountry id="C8D57625A775BE3AFC01FB4C45372650" box="[973,1131,1267,1293]" name="Taiwan Island" pageId="3" pageNumber="195">Taiwan Island</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation id="28F92A30A775BE3AFBB0FB4C458E2650" box="[1148,1234,1267,1293]" captionStart="FIGURE 28" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1722,1746]" captionTargetBox="[164,1423,273,1699]" captionTargetId="figure-61@7.[164,1423,273,1699]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 28. Known distribution of Platysodes Westwood, 1873 species (inset photograph shows the dead specimen of P. ma- doni Bourgoin, 1923 found at Mount Fanjingshan, Guizhou, China, provided by Ka-Chen Ou-Yang). Distribution data take from Qiu et al. (2015) and specimens examined in the present work." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4301825" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4301825/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="195">Fig. 28</figureCitation>
). Furthermore, an individual of 
<taxonomicName id="77C24D36A775BE3AFEFDFAA8408D266C" authorityName="H. Kobayashi" authorityYear="1989" box="[305,465,1303,1329]" class="Insecta" family="Cetoniidae" genus="Platysodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="195" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="formosanus">
<emphasis id="82B6EAA7A775BE3AFEFDFAA8408D266C" box="[305,465,1303,1329]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="195">P. formosanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
bearing an indistinct macula on elytron (nearly disappeared) was found from 
<collectingCountry id="C8D57625A775BE3AFA86FAA844C0266C" box="[1354,1436,1303,1329]" name="Taiwan" pageId="3" pageNumber="195">Taiwan</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation id="28F92A30A775BE3AFF6CFA8441AF2608" box="[160,243,1338,1365]" captionStart="FIGURES 24–27" captionStartId="6.[151,264,913,937]" captionTargetBox="[171,1413,185,883]" captionTargetId="figure-17@6.[165,1422,181,889]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 24–27. Habitus of Platysodes Westwood, 1873 species in oblique view. 24, P. sabatinellii Qiu &amp; Xu, new species (CKSJ); 25, P. formosanus Kobayashi, 1990 (slightly greasy, CKSJ); 26, P. jansoni Arrow, 1910 (CKSJ); 27, P. verlorenii Westwood, 1873 (greasy, CKSJ)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4301823" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4301823/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="195">Fig. 25</figureCitation>
), and a female of 
<taxonomicName id="77C24D36A775BE3AFE70FA8443752609" authorityName="Arrow, M. O. de Lisle" authorityYear="1910" box="[444,553,1339,1364]" class="Insecta" family="Cetoniidae" genus="Platysodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="195" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jansoni">
<emphasis id="82B6EAA7A775BE3AFE70FA8443752609" box="[444,553,1339,1364]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="195">P. jansoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with two maculae was discovered from 
<collectingCountry id="C8D57625A775BE3AFC23FA8445122608" box="[1007,1102,1339,1365]" name="Vietnam" pageId="3" pageNumber="195">Vietnam</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation id="28F92A30A775BE3AFB91FA8445EC2608" box="[1117,1200,1339,1365]" captionStart="FIGURES 9–17" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1868,1892]" captionTargetBox="[221,1368,275,1835]" captionTargetId="figure-69@4.[213,1374,273,1845]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 9–17. Specimens of Platysodes Westwood, 1873. 9–12, P. formosanus Kobayashi, 1990: 9, female habitus (MYNU); 10–11, slightly greasy male and distal declivity of elytra (CKSJ); 12, parameres of holotype in apical view (MSMT; provided by Yu-Tang Wang). 13–17, P. jansoni Arrow, 1910: 13, greasy female with two maculae on elytron (BPBM; provided by James H. Boone); 14, female habitus (CKSJ); 15–16, male habitus and distal declivity of elytra (MNHN); 17, parameres in apical view (provided by Christophe Rivier). Red arrows emphasize the tomentose maculae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4301819" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4301819/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="195">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
). The two specimens have here verified the prediction proposed by 
<bibRefCitation id="D4534B44A775BE3AFD55FAE042082624" author="Qiu, J. Y. &amp; Xu, H. &amp; Chen, L." box="[665,852,1374,1401]" pageId="3" pageNumber="195" pagination="553 - 564" refId="ref4697" refString="Qiu, J. Y., Xu, H. &amp; Chen, L. (2015) Review of the Oriental genus Platysodes Westwood (Coleoptera: Scarabaeidae: Cetoniinae: Cremastocheilini) with a redescription of Platysodes madoni Bourgoin. Zootaxa, 4021 (4), 553 - 564. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4021.4.5" type="journal article" year="2015">
Qiu 
<emphasis id="82B6EAA7A775BE3AFD06FAE0425E2624" box="[714,770,1375,1401]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="195">et al.</emphasis>
(2015)
</bibRefCitation>
that the variability of tomentose maculae on elytron can be observed in a species of wide distribution. Therefore, neither endemism of 
<taxonomicName id="77C24D36A775BE3AFBE5FA3C459B26C0" authorityName="H. Kobayashi" authorityYear="1989" box="[1065,1223,1411,1437]" class="Insecta" family="Cetoniidae" genus="Platysodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="195" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="formosanus">
<emphasis id="82B6EAA7A775BE3AFBE5FA3C459B26C0" box="[1065,1223,1411,1437]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="195">P. formosanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
nor morphological differences between the two species are well established, but we would like to formally propose the synonymy when sufficient material got rather than synonymize them at present.
</paragraph>
